RED WINE QUALITY EXPLORATION by FELIPE BARROS

This dataset is one of the datasets created on the paper “Modeling wine preferences by data mining from physicochemical properties” [Cortez et al., 2009]. The inputs include objective tests, such as PH values, and the output is based on sensory data, gathered from at least 3 wine expert evaluations. The output value ranges from 0 (very bad) to 10 (very excellent). The wines are variants of the Portuguese “Vinho Verde” wine. This particular dataset contains information regarding the red wines.

There are 1599 different wines, 11 features and 1 output value (quality). Information about the features and the output value is the following (provided by the original authors):

Input variables (based on physicochemical tests):

  • 1 - fixed acidity (tartaric acid - g / dm^3)
  • 2 - volatile acidity (acetic acid - g / dm^3)
  • 3 - citric acid (g / dm^3)
  • 4 - residual sugar (g / dm^3)
  • 5 - chlorides (sodium chloride - g / dm^3
  • 6 - free sulfur dioxide (mg / dm^3)
  • 7 - total sulfur dioxide (mg / dm^3)
  • 8 - density (g / cm^3)
  • 9 - pH
  • 10 - sulphates (potassium sulphate - g / dm3)
  • 11 - alcohol (% by volume)

Output variable (based on sensory data):

  • 12 - quality (score between 0 and 10)

Description of the features and output value is the following (also provided by the original authors):

  • 1 - fixed acidity: most acids involved with wine or fixed or nonvolatile (do not evaporate readily)
  • 2 - volatile acidity: the amount of acetic acid in wine, which at too high of levels can lead to an unpleasant, vinegar taste
  • 3 - citric acid: found in small quantities, citric acid can add ‘freshness’ and flavor to wines
  • 4 - residual sugar: the amount of sugar remaining after fermentation stops, it’s rare to find wines with less than 1 gram/liter and wines with greater than 45 grams/liter are considered sweet
  • 5 - chlorides: the amount of salt in the wine
  • 6 - free sulfur dioxide: the free form of SO2 exists in equilibrium between molecular SO2 (as a dissolved gas) and bisulfite ion; it prevents microbial growth and the oxidation of wine
  • 7 - total sulfur dioxide: amount of free and bound forms of S02; in low concentrations, SO2 is mostly undetectable in wine, but at free SO2 concentrations over 50 ppm, SO2 becomes evident in the nose and taste of wine
  • 8 - density: the density of water is close to that of water depending on the percent alcohol and sugar content
  • 9 - pH: describes how acidic or basic a wine is on a scale from 0 (very acidic) to 14 (very basic); most wines are between 3-4 on the pH scale
  • 10 - sulphates: a wine additive which can contribute to sulfur dioxide gas (S02) levels, wich acts as an antimicrobial and antioxidant
  • 11 - alcohol: the percent alcohol content of the wine
  • 12 - quality (score between 0 and 10)

The dataset consists of 11 numerical features and 1 integer feature (quality). The X feature just represents the index of the observation on the data frame.

On the summary it is possible to identify some initial trends on the data. For example, there are some features that seem to have outliers on them, such as: volatile acidity, citric acid, redisual sugar, chlorides, free sulfur dioxide, total sulfur dioxide, and sulphates. Also, most of the wines are of average quality (the 1st quartile border equals 5, the median equals 6 and the third quartile border equals 6).

## 
##   3   4   5   6   7   8 
##  10  53 681 638 199  18

Out of 1599 wines, 63 (~4%) are of quality 3 or 4, 1319 (~82.5%) are of quality 5 or 6 and 217 (~13,6%) are of quality 7 or 8.

Histograms will help visualize distribution patterns for the other features as well.

These histograms help us visualize how some of the features on the dataset have outliers, given that some of them are right tailed. Chlorides is a good example of this characteristic. Most of the data is around 0.05 and 0.15, with very few examples of wine going up to 6.

Also, most of the data is relatively normal, with the exception of citric acid.

Let’s transform some of the features using a log scale to try and get better visualizations of them. Suitable choices would be residual sugar, chlorides, free sulfur dioxide, total sulfur dioxide, and sulphates.

With log transformation it is easier to identify patterns on these features. With the exception of free sulfur dioxide, they all have normal-like distributions.

Univariate Analysis

The dataset consists of 1599 observations of red wines with information about 11 physicochemical properties and 1 information about the quality of each wine. The pyhisicochemial information was collected with experiments and the quality of each wine is a mean of a value provided by different wine experts. All the information is in the form of numbers.

The quality values were given in a scale from 0 (very bad) to 10 (very excellent). However, the majority of the wines have quality of 5 or 6. The worst wine has a quality of 3. The best wine has a quality of 8.

Some features are long-tailed. Examples are residual sugar, chlorides, free sulfur dioxide, total sulfur dioxide, and sulphates.

With a few exceptions, the features have a distribution close to normal.

Since quality is the output feature of the study that generated this dataset, the feature is undoubtly the main feature of interest.

For the variance observed in some of these features and their nature in relation to overall taste in wine, I would describe residual sugar, density and pH as features of interest.

So far, I did not create any new variables from existing variables in the dataset.

I’ve established some features of interest, but that was mainly done looking at their distribution and common wine knowledge. It would be best to evaluate the correlation between the features, to identify if the choices made are the best ones or if there is some possible feature worth considering.

Based on correlations, the best features to predict the quality of a wine are, in order, alcohol, volatile acidity and sulphates. My initial intuition was that residual sugar, density and pH would better describe the quality of a wine, with alcohol and acidity features as possible features to look afterwards. These initial findings show that there is more to the quality of a wine than what common knowledge says.

With the correlation knowledge, I’ll try now to visualize the influence of those features on the quality of the wines.

The scatterplot suggests that as the percentage of alcohol increases so does the overall quality of the wine, as shown by the linear regression line. Even when comparing quality of 5 and 6 (the most common on the dataset), the observations tend to go up on quality 6, whilst being clumped below the regression line on quality 5.

The boxplot also supports that theory. Wines with better quality have higher median and higher mean (shown as red crosses).

Volatile acidity is the opposite as alcohol: as it increases, the overall quality of the wine decreases. Since the correlation found was negative (around -0.39), that was expected.

Again, the boxplots suggests the same and provide additional information (mean and median values for each quality). As the level of volatile acidity decreases, the perceived quality of the wine increases.

The top 1% for sulphates was removed for better visualization. For sulphates, the scatterplot has a behavior similar to alcohol: better quality wines have higher levels of sulphates.

The boxplot for each quality supports that trend. All the higher qualities have a higher mean and median values of sulphates.

By plotting these three features on scatterplots and boxplots against quality, it is easier to visualize their influence on the quality of the wines. By now, it is safe to say that better wines probably have higher alcohol and sulphates levels, whilst having a lower volatile acidity level.

Since citric acid is the fourth most correlated feature to quality, it is worth doing some analysis on it.

The correlation between citric acid and quality (~0.226) is not much different from the correlation between sulphates and quality (~0.25), so their tendencies are also similar to each other. Better wines tend to have, on average, higher levels of citric acid.

For the boxplot between citric acid and quality, we can see a clear difference between better wines (quality of 7 and 8) and the other ones. Not only they tend to have higher values of citric acid, the majority of their observations (over 75%) are over 0.25g/dm^3 of citric acid.

Since density is a feature most commonly used when describing “the body” of the wine, I’ll do a similar analysis for it.

The top 1% for density was removed for better visualization. Since the correlation between these features is very low (around -0.17), the influence of density on the quality of the wine is lower than previous features. It seems that using density to evaluate the quality of a wine (a common practice of non-experts) is not the best approach.

The boxplot adds a little more information. There is a decrease of density levels on better wines, but that is only noticeable with quality levels of 7 and 8. For the other quality levels, there doesn’t seem to be a significant difference.

Bivariate Analysis

I’ve investigated the relationships between quality and alcohol, volatile acidity, sulphates, citric acid and density. In terms of correlation with quality, they were, in order, 1st, 2nd, 3rd, 4th and 6th most correlated features of the dataset. The first four were chosen because of they closer relationship with quality and density was chosen out of personal curiosity.

Alcohol was the feature most correlated with quality, with a factor of 0.48. The positive correlation between them implied that increasing the level of alcohol would increase the perceived quality of the wine. The plots created demonstrated that assumption.

Volatile acidity was the second feature most correlated with quality, with a factor of -0.39. The negative correlation implies a decrease of one when an increase in the other occurs. The plots generated help visualize that relationship. As volatile acidity levels go down, the quality of the wines go up.

Sulphates and citric acid where the third and fourth most correlated qualities, with factors of 0.25 and 0.226, respectively. Higher levels of these features are correlated with better quality of the wine, although their influence is not as strong as the influence of alcohol and volatile acidity.

Density was the sixth most correlated feature with quality. The choice to visualize the influence of that feature was mostly curiosity based, since the correlation factor is of only -0.175. Although there is an influence of the feature on the quality of the wine, that influence is only noteworthy on the best wines on the dataset (7 or above). Those wines tend to have a lower density value.

Features related to acidity naturally seem to be correlated with each other. Examples are fixed acidity, volatile acidity, citric acid and pH. Density also seems to be related with those features, along with residual sugar and alcohol.

The strongest relationship found was between fixed acidity and pH, with a factor of 0.683. That is not a surprising relationship, as one feature (pH) is evaluated based on properties of the other (acidity).

Multivariate Plots Section

To help visualization for the next plots, I’ll divide the wines on baskets, based on their quality. The baskets are:

  • Bad: 4 or lower quality
  • Average: 5 quality
  • Good: 6 quality
  • Best: 7 or over quality

The choice of breaks for the baskets are based on the fact that most observations on the dataset have quality of 5 or 6.

## 
##     Bad Average    Good    Best 
##      63     681     638     217

The top 1% values for volatile acidity were removed on this plot. The vertical and horizontal lines are the medians for alcohol and volatile acidity, respectively. By using both lines, the graph is divided into four quadrants. We can see how alcohol has a higher influence in the quality factor as most of red and green dots (bad and average wines) are on the second or third quadrants, where alcohol levels are lower. The first quadrant has a good number of good wines but also has some presence of bad and average wines. The fourth quadrant, where alcohol is high and volatile acidity is low is the best quadrant, as expected: most purple dots (best wines) are present there.

By swaping volatile acidity for density on the y-axis, the pattern is similar, but with even more bias towards the x-axis (alcohol). The vertical line (the median for alcohol) seems to be the only one dividing most of the good ones from the bad ones. This again goes against common knowledge that density is a good feature for telling the quality of a wine.

This plot also has a difference between the quadrants. In this case, the second quadrant (high sulphates and low volatile acidity) is where most of the best wines (purple dots) are.

So far, the only categorical feature in the dataset was quality, that was reduced into buckets. I’ve noticed that having almost all the variables with continuous values might conceal some interesting information. For example, is there a difference in how the density affects the quality of the wine in different levels of alcohol?

I’ll bucket wines by alcohol levels and investigate some more.

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##    8.40    9.50   10.20   10.42   11.10   14.90

A reminder of the summary for alcohol values on the dataset. The value range is of 6.5 (14.9 minues 8.4). By dividing alcohol levels into three buckets, that would imply in a step of around 2.16 for each bucket. I’ll round it to 2.15 and use that value as a step to the cut. The buckets will be cut as follows:

  • Low alcohol level: over 8.4% or under or equal to 9.55%
  • Medium alcohol level: over 9.55% or under or equal to 11.7%
  • High alcohol level: over 11.7%
## 
##    Low Alcohol Medium Alcohol   High Alcohol 
##            438            949            212

The dataset is mostly of medium alcohol levels, based on the cut parameters. However, there is a reasonable number of observations for the other buckets.

The top 1% for both axes were removed for this plot, in order to better visualize it. By dividing the alcohol levels into buckets, we can see not only how the quality of the wines are distributed in the buckets but also the distrubution of sulphates and volatile acidity. The high alcohol bucket has almost only good and best wines and most of the observations are on the fourth quadrant. On the opposite side, the low alcohol bucket has almost only average wines and most of the observations are on the second and third quadrants. The plot depicts at the same time the influence of the three features most impactful on the quality of a wine.

As a last exploration attempt, I’ll try to also cut by density.

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##  0.9901  0.9956  0.9968  0.9967  0.9978  1.0037

The variance in density levels is 0.0136. By diving in three equal steps, we’ve got roughly 0.0045 for each step. However, the first step doesn’t even surpass the first quartile, and the second goes from there to beyond the third. That would create a bucket with the majority of the observations. Looking to create more even buckets, I’ll use the values from the first quartile, median and third quartile.

## 
##  Light Medium  Heavy 
##    407    788    404

The distribution seems more balanced, even with the middle bucket with almost double the number of observations of the other buckets. The buckets are represented in the following manner:

  • Light wines: up to 0.9956g/cm^3
  • Medium wines: higher than 0.9956g/cm^3 and up to 0.9978g/cm^3
  • Heavy wines: higher than 0.9978g/cm^3

Lower density levels are correlated with better wine. In the low density bucket, most of the wines are good or best, as expected. They also are higher on alcohol levels. The medium density bucket is a surprise, as it has a more dense cloud of average wines than the high density bucket.

Multivariate Analysis

By looking simultaneously at several features and their relationship with quality, it was possible to see how each other contribute to the quality of the wine. Since the three best features to try to predict the quality of the wine are alcohol, volatile acidity and sulphates, creating a plot with the relationship between them and quality efficiently described the properties of a good wine.

To improve the analysis, I decided to divide alcohol and density into buckets. That allowed me to visualize multiple features interacting with each other at the same time.

A surprising interaction was found when density values were cut into buckets. Even though a linear regression model suggests that low density levels are correlated with better wine, the middle bucket seemed worst than the heavy bucket.

Final Plots and Summary

This is the best plot to represent the dataset. We can see how alcohol heavily influences the quality of the wine by the difference of observations on each bucket. The median lines for Acetic Acid and Potassium Sulphate also help to illustrate how these features work in relation to the quality of the wine. More acetic acid gives a vinegar taste to the wine, so most wines above the horizontal line are Bad or Average. Potassium Sulphate helps with antimicrobial and antioxidant effects on wine, giving them an overall better quality. Because of that, wines on the right of the vertical line are more likely to be Good or Best.

The second plot I’ve chosen to describe the data is the one above. The reason I’ve chosen it is because most people (myself included) are not experts on wine, and most of them believe that the density of the wine is somehow related to its quality. Although that is true, density has a positive correlation with the quality of the wine, the influence of density on the quality is low. Lighter wines are more likely to be Good or Best, but Medium and Heavy wines are more or less the same on that regard.

These boxplots are a great description of the most influential feature on regarding to the quality of a wine: alcohol. With the strongest correlation with quality, variance in the levels of alcohol between wines is what best separates the worst wines from the best ones.

Reflection

This was my first solo attempt at an Exploratory Data Analysis. The data used consisted of physicochemical properties and quality of wines. Since my knowledge of wine was close to none, I as mostly looking at the data without much assumptions. The only thing that I thought I knew was that people use the density of the wine to describe its “body”, and that might be related to its quality.

As I went along with the exploration, I’ve discovered what features are more correlated with quality and if that correlation was positive or negative. I was surprised to discover that density was correlated, but not much. I had only one assumption and it turned out to be false!

The multivariate analysis was not easy to perform. Some of my first plots were not describing the data correctly, I used features on wrong axes, was not taking much out of them. Then, I decided to include the vertical and horizontal lines for the median values for each axis. After that, the information was clearer and the analysis was easier to make.

I’ve encountered two problems while doing this exploration. The first was that quality was the only naturally categorical feature. That limited my analysis at first, but I tried to go around that by creating two categorical features, derived from original features on the dataset. I think that, because of that, I was able to go further on my analysis. The second problem was the natural distribution of the data: most wines were of quality 5 or 6, with none below 3 or above 8. That was not a problem I could solve in any way I can think of. It wasn’t even a big problem, but it is necessary to address the results from this analysis with caution, as it could not be a good representation for other datasets of red wines.

Going further, some chemistry background knowledge could prove useful on trying to create more derived features. Maybe there is a relationship between the features on the dataset that I am not aware of. In reality, I’ve reserved most of the investigation to the three most correlated features and density (to address my only assumption). There could be much more hidden in the data I’m simply not yet experienced enough to unveil.
